excerpt: Striking, early 21st–century museum focusing on Canadian & international human rights issues.
detail_description: The Canadian Museum for Human Rights is a modern museum that focuses on both Canadian and international human rights issues. Located in Winnipeg, it is one of the city's many attractions, offering visitors a unique experience with its striking architecture. The building features a glass cloud facade, a Tower of Hope spire, and massive limestone roots that symbolize the journey towards universal human rights.
name: Canadian Museum for Human Rights
address: 85 Israel Asper Way, Winnipeg, MB R3C 0L5, Canada

excerpt: Sizable museum featuring European paintings, contemporary artwork & Inuit sculptures.
detail_description: The Winnipeg Art Gallery is a significant museum housing an extensive collection of European paintings, contemporary artwork, and Inuit sculptures. One of its highlights is Qaumajuq, an extension featuring the largest public collection of contemporary Inuit art globally. The space showcases modern-day and historic carvings in a captivating circular, multi-layered glass display. Visitors can freely explore the installation in the WAG's lobby and engage with an interactive display providing detailed information about the art pieces.
name: Winnipeg Art Gallery
address: 300 Memorial Blvd, Winnipeg, MB R3C 1V1, Canada

excerpt: Sizable museum with exhibits on planetary & human history, with bones, dioramas & a planetarium.
detail_description: The Manitoba Museum is a large museum featuring exhibits on planetary and human history, including bones, dioramas, and a planetarium. The museum's galleries highlight the connection between people and the natural environment in Manitoba through artifacts, written and audio information, interactive displays, and dioramas. Visitors can explore Manitoba's distinct ecosystems such as Arctic/Sub-Arctic, Boreal Forest, Parklands, and Grasslands.
name: Manitoba Museum
address: 190 Rupert Ave, Winnipeg, MB R3B 0N2, Canada

excerpt: One of 2 national mints, this facility offers tours & exhibits about the coin manufacturing process.
detail_description: The Royal Canadian Mint, located in Winnipeg near the southern border of the province, is one of two national mints in Canada. Visitors can take tours and explore exhibits to learn about the coin manufacturing process. Winnipeg itself offers a variety of attractions including the Assiniboine Park Zoo and the Canadian Museum for Human Rights. The city also hosts annual festivals such as Festival du Voyageur in February and the Icelandic Festival of Manitoba in summer.
name: Royal Canadian Mint
address: 520 Lagimodiere Blvd, Winnipeg, MB R2J 3E7, Canada

excerpt: Enduring zoo established in 1904, with a polar bear habitat, restaurant, gift shop & steam train.
detail_description: Established in 1904, Assiniboine Park Zoo is a prominent attraction located in Winnipeg, near the southern border of Manitoba. The zoo spans 80 acres and houses over 200 animal species from around the world. One of its main highlights is the award-winning Journey to Churchill exhibit, which opened in 2014.
name: Assiniboine Park Zoo
address: 2595 Roblin Blvd, Winnipeg, MB R3R 2N7, Canada

excerpt: This 640-acre urban green space offers wildlife, lakes, a cafe, a shop, a nature center & more.
detail_description: FortWhyte Alive, a 640-acre urban wilderness oasis in Manitoba's capital city, offers a plethora of outdoor activities such as fishing, paddling, snowshoeing, ice skating, skiing, and tobogganing. Visitors can explore the diverse wildlife including bison, whitetail deer, reptiles, muskrats and over 160 bird species. The park also features cultural and historical exhibits along with a farm and restaurant.
name: FortWhyte Alive
address: 1961 McCreary Rd, Winnipeg, MB R3P 2K9, Canada

excerpt: Built in 1920, this neoclassical government building houses the Legislative Assembly of Manitoba.
detail_description: The Manitoba Legislative Building, constructed in 1920, is a neoclassical government building that serves as the home of the Legislative Assembly of Manitoba. Designed by Frank Worthington Simon, it features impressive architecture including massive columns, intricate carvings, and a majestic dome. The exterior is adorned with various works of art representing wisdom, justice, and courage. The building also houses the Manitoba Legislative Museum and is recognized for the Golden Boy statue atop its dome symbolizing progress.
name: Manitoba Legislative Building
address: 450 Broadway, Winnipeg, MB R3C 0V8, Canada

excerpt: Sprawling park featuring a zoo, conservatory, outdoor theatre, play equipment & other attractions.
detail_description: Assiniboine Park is one of Winnipeg's largest parks, offering a variety of attractions such as a zoo, conservatory, outdoor theatre, and play equipment. It's an ideal spot for picnics with its wide-open fields and wooded areas. The park hosts free concerts in the summer at the Lyric Theatre and features beautiful gardens. Visitors can also enjoy dining at the Qualico Family Centre's Park Cafe or explore art galleries and event spaces at the Tudor-style Pavilion.
name: Assiniboine Park
address: 55 Pavilion Crescent, Winnipeg, MB R3P 2N6, Canada

detail_description: When visiting Winnipeg, Manitoba, a trip to The Forks is a must. This historic meeting place sits at the confluence of the Red and Assiniboine rivers and offers an energetic blend of people, food, and culture. Spend a full day exploring this vibrant area where you can indulge in sweet treats like Funfetti ice cream at Fete Ice Cream & Coffee or Instagram-worthy desserts at Jenna Rae Cakes with edible glitter.
name: The Forks
address: Winnipeg, MB, Canada

detail_description: Thermëa by Nordik Spa-Nature is a popular spa in Winnipeg that offers a day of relaxation and thermotherapy. The indoor/outdoor space features pools of warm water, ice cold plunge pools, steam rooms, aromatherapy, saunas, exfoliation rooms, and more. Based on the concept of thermal hydrotherapy and relaxation techniques, visitors can experience hot and cold treatments followed by rest in lounging areas or napping rooms.
name: Thermea Spa Village Winnipeg
address: 775 Crescent Dr, Winnipeg, MB R3T 1X3, Canada

excerpt: Large riverside community hub with a variety of shopping, dining & recreational activities.
detail_description: Located at the meeting point of the Assiniboine and Red rivers in Winnipeg, The Forks Market is a vibrant community hub offering an array of shopping, dining, and recreational activities. This historic site has evolved into a trendy destination featuring The Common, a gourmet food hall with communal tables and diverse culinary offerings by regional chefs.
name: The Forks Market
address: 1 Forks Market Rd, Winnipeg, MB R3C 4L9, Canada

excerpt: Established in 1974, this museum displays numerous planes & aviation artifacts in a 1930s hangar.
detail_description: The Royal Aviation Museum of Western Canada, located in Winnipeg, Manitoba, is a top-notch facility housed in a 1930s hangar. With 22 aircraft and 14 immersive galleries, the museum showcases Canada's remarkable contributions to aviation. It serves as an ideal location due to Winnipeg's historical significance as a hub for trade and commerce. The museum also hosts special exhibitions such as 'Snoopy and the Red Baron,' celebrating the beloved Peanuts character's World War Flying Ace persona.
name: Royal Aviation Museum of Western Canada
address: 2088 Wellington Ave, Winnipeg, MB R3H 1C1, Canada

excerpt: 9-acre park on the Red River with local history exhibits & art, plus a playground & amphitheatre.
detail_description: The Forks National Historic Site features stunning scenery and interesting history, including a market and museums. The park is home to aboriginal people for thousands of years and it's now a popular tourist destination. Throughout the year there are many events happening at the site that families can enjoy.
name: The Forks National Historic Site
address: Forks Market Rd, Winnipeg, MB R3C 4S8, Canada

excerpt: This Roman Catholic basilica was built in 1972 behind the surviving facade of an earlier church.
detail_description: Saint Boniface Cathedral, a Roman Catholic basilica, was constructed in 1972 behind the remaining facade of an earlier church. It is a popular spot for engagement photos due to its historic and grand atmosphere. The cathedral offers picturesque photo spaces such as the grounds, rose gardens, and views of the Red River. Visitors can explore the unique architecture of the present-day Cathedral built within the ruins of Western Canada's oldest basilica.
name: Saint Boniface Cathedral
address: 180 De La Cathedrale Ave, Winnipeg, MB R2H 0H7, Canada

excerpt: Landscaped garden featuring namesake artist's bronze sculptures with flowers, benches & fountains.
detail_description: The Leo Mol Sculpture Garden, situated in Assiniboine Park in Winnipeg, Canada, is a must-visit for art enthusiasts and nature lovers alike. This beautifully landscaped garden showcases over 300 breathtaking sculptures by the renowned artist Leo Mol. Visitors can admire bronze and ceramic sculptures, as well as paintings and drawings set amidst picturesque plant beds, paths, and ponds.
name: Leo Mol Sculpture Garden
address: Assiniboine Park Dr, Winnipeg, MB R3P 2N7, Canada

excerpt: Built in 1822 as a trading post, this park offers the original fort gate, green space & light shows.
detail_description: Upper Fort Garry Provincial Park, located in Winnipeg, is a unique combination of park, sculpture, and technology that showcases the history of a significant fur trading post. The park features the original fort gate dating back to the 1850s and offers green space for visitors to enjoy. Through strategically placed garden beds and an engraved wall of weathering steel, the park tells the story of its strategic importance in Manitoba's history.
name: Upper Fort Garry
address: 130 Main St, Winnipeg, MB R3C 1A4, Canada

detail_description: Qaumajuq is a remarkable $65-million Inuit art center located at the Winnipeg Art Gallery. The building's striking design resembles a massive snowdrift attached to the original angular structure of the gallery. Inside, visitors can explore galleries that pay homage to the expansive beauty of the north and showcase an internationally acclaimed collection of over 27,000 works spanning from the Renaissance to contemporary Indigenous artists.
name: Qaumajuq
address: 300 Memorial Blvd, Winnipeg, MB R3C 1V1, Canada

excerpt: Cozy, lower-level spot with stone walls serving creative brunch fare plus breakfast cocktails.
detail_description: Clementine Cafe is a trendy spot located in the Exchange District of Winnipeg, offering a cozy and hip atmosphere with its lower-level setting, stone walls, and 70s-style wallpaper. The cafe is known for its creative brunch fare and breakfast cocktails. Owned by Carolina Konrad and her sister Raya, who previously worked at Segovia, this cafe serves up some of the best meals in the city.
name: Clementine Cafe
address: 123 Princess St, Winnipeg, MB R3B 1K8, Canada

excerpt: Plant & wildlife preserve with an interpretive center, walking trails & children's play equipment.
detail_description: The Living Prairie Museum in Winnipeg offers a unique experience to explore the remnants of the tall grass prairie ecosystem. Spanning 13 hectares, it is home to over 150 grass and wildflower species as well as various prairie wildlife. Visitors can witness the annual migration of Monarch butterflies, participate in seed collection activities, and embark on self-guided hikes to uncover the secrets of the tall grass prairie. The museum also features an interpretive center with seasonal activities for all ages.
name: Living Prairie Museum
address: Ness Ave, 2795 Ness Ave, Winnipeg, MB R3J 3S4, Canada

excerpt: The Exchange District is known for its cultural offerings, including ballet and opera at the Centennial Concert Hall, plays at the Royal Manitoba Theatre Centre, and the Manitoba Museum’s hands-on science exhibits and planetarium. Vintage and indie boutiques line King and Arthur Streets. Trendy eateries serve global-inspired tapas or sushi, while hip nightclubs and cocktail lounges cater to young professionals.
detail_description: The Exchange District in Winnipeg is a vibrant cultural hub with a variety of entertainment options. Visitors can enjoy ballet and opera performances at the Centennial Concert Hall, watch plays at the Royal Manitoba Theatre Centre, and explore hands-on science exhibits at the Manitoba Museum. The area is also known for its vintage and indie boutiques along King and Arthur Streets, as well as trendy eateries serving global-inspired tapas and sushi. At night, young professionals can unwind at hip nightclubs and cocktail lounges.
name: Exchange District
address: Winnipeg, MB, Canada

detail_description: Festival du Voyageur Inc. is a 10-day winter celebration in Winnipeg, Manitoba, paying homage to the fur trading industry. This event features music, arts, crafts, folklore, and dance that showcase the unique heritage and culture of the region. Initially a three-day festival with 50,000 visitors in 1970, it has now become Western Canada's largest winter festival held every February.
name: Festival du Voyageur Inc.
address: 233 Provencher Blvd, Winnipeg, MB R2H 0G4, Canada

detail_description: Located in Winnipeg's Assiniboine Park, The Leaf is a must-visit attraction that offers an immersive experience for families. This outdoor garden complex features six distinct gardens, including the Indigenous Peoples Garden, Kitchen Garden, Sensory Garden, Performance Garden, Seasonal Garden, and the Grove. It is the first garden in North America to showcase Canadian cultural stories through plants.
name: The Leaf
address: 145 The Leaf Wy., Winnipeg, MB R3P 2N6, Canada

excerpt: Winnipeg is the capital of the Canadian province of Manitoba. Its heart is The Forks, a historic site at the intersection of the Red and Assiniboine rivers, with warehouses converted to shops and restaurants, plus ample green space dedicated to festivals, concerts and exhibits. Nearby, the Exchange District is known for its well-preserved, early 20th-century architecture and numerous art galleries.
detail_description: Winnipeg, the capital of Manitoba, Canada, is a vibrant city with a rich cultural scene and diverse attractions. The Forks, located at the confluence of the Red and Assiniboine rivers, offers a blend of history and modern amenities including shops, restaurants, and green spaces for events. The nearby Exchange District boasts well-preserved early 20th-century architecture and numerous art galleries.
name: Winnipeg
address: Manitoba, Canada

excerpt: Artifacts relating to French-speaking & Métis societies, housed in a historic former convent.
detail_description: Le Musée de Saint-Boniface Museum, also known as the St. Boniface Museum, is located in the oldest building in Winnipeg, which was once a convent for the Grey Nuns. The museum showcases an extensive collection of artifacts that offer insights into the lives and culture of early Francophone and Métis communities in Manitoba. Visitors can explore exhibits dedicated to Louis Riel, a prominent Métis leader considered the father of Manitoba.
name: Le Musée de Saint-Boniface Museum
address: temporarily closed, 494 Tache Avenue, 219 Provencher Blvd, Winnipeg, MB R2H 2B2, Canada

excerpt: Founded in 1881, this cultural hub on 20 city blocks offers historic buildings, restaurants & shops.
detail_description: The Exchange District BIZ, established in 1881, is a cultural hub spanning 20 city blocks in Winnipeg. It boasts historic buildings that have been repurposed into independent boutiques, restaurants, and cocktail bars. The area's charm lies in its turn-of-the-20th-century warehouse architecture and early skyscrapers influenced by Chicago style. Hollywood often chooses this district as a backdrop for 1920s gangster movies due to its authentic atmosphere.
name: Exchange District BIZ
address: 492 Main St, Winnipeg, MB R3B 1B7, Canada

excerpt: Themed, interactive exhibits for children, along with a dedicated space for toddlers.
detail_description: The Manitoba Children's Museum is a delightful haven for young explorers, nestled in the historic Kinsmen building, which once served as a train repair depot. Since its opening in 1983, this vibrant museum has captivated children with themed and interactive exhibits designed to ignite their imaginations. With twelve permanent galleries, kids can embark on exciting adventures like climbing the towering Lasagna Lookout or experimenting with water at the Splash Lab.
name: Children's Museum
address: 45 Forks Market Rd, Winnipeg, MB R3C 4T6, Canada

detail_description: When visiting Winnipeg, one of the must-experience activities is catching a game by the Winnipeg Jets Hockey Club. As one of Canada's seven NHL teams, they bring an electrifying atmosphere to every match at Canada Life Centre. The hockey season runs from October through April, featuring over 40 home games that promise high energy and excitement. Fans create an unforgettable experience regardless of the game's outcome, making it a fantastic outing for sports enthusiasts.
name: Winnipeg Jets Hockey Club
address: 260 Hargrave St, Winnipeg, MB R3C 5S5, Canada

excerpt: Urban green space with an outdoor pool, picnic & BBQ facilities, play structures & a restaurant.
detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Winnipeg, Kildonan Park is a picturesque urban green space offering a variety of outdoor activities and recreational opportunities. The park features an outdoor pool, picnic and BBQ facilities, play structures, and a restaurant. Visitors can explore enchanting areas such as the Witch's Hut inspired by The Brothers Grimm, charming foot bridges over streams, and the iconic Rainbow Stage open-air theatre.
name: Kildonan Park
address: 2015 Main St, Winnipeg, MB R2V 1P4, Canada

detail_description: Nestled along the banks of the Red River in Whittier Park, Fort Gibraltar is a captivating re-creation of the original North West Company fort established in 1810. This historical gem offers visitors a glimpse into its vibrant past, marked by events such as its destruction by the Hudson's Bay Company and subsequent rebuilding.
name: Fort Gibraltar Weddings and Events
address: 866 Rue St Joseph, Winnipeg, MB R2H 0G4, Canada

excerpt: The Royal Manitoba Theatre Centre's 789-seat John Hirsch Mainstage hosts a variety of plays.
detail_description: The Royal Manitoba Theatre Centre is a vibrant cultural hub located just a short drive from Winnipeg, making it an ideal stop for theatre enthusiasts. With its impressive 789-seat John Hirsch Mainstage, the venue showcases a diverse array of plays that cater to various tastes. Visitors can easily combine their trip with explorations of nearby attractions like The Forks National Historic Site and the Canadian Museum for Human Rights.
name: Royal Manitoba Theatre Centre
address: 174 Market Ave, Winnipeg, MB R3B 0P8, Canada

excerpt: Dog-friendly urban forest with some marked hiking & biking trails, a pond & parking lot.
detail_description: Assiniboine Forest is a dog-friendly urban oasis in Winnipeg, offering marked hiking and biking trails, a serene pond, and convenient parking. Nestled within the city limits, this lush forest provides a tranquil escape for nature enthusiasts and pet owners. Visitors can explore well-maintained paths while keeping an eye out for the native whitetail deer that roam the area. The forest's peaceful ambiance makes it an ideal location for outdoor activities such as walking or cycling.
name: Assiniboine Forest
address: 2595 Roblin Blvd, Winnipeg, MB R3P 2N7, Canada

excerpt: Casino offering slot machines, bingo & casual dining, plus concerts & live events.
detail_description: Nestled in Winnipeg, Club Regent Casino is a vibrant hub of entertainment that beautifully blends traditional gaming with modern flair. With over 900 slot machines, including a plethora of penny slots, it caters to both casual players and high rollers alike. The casino's tropical theme creates an inviting atmosphere where guests can enjoy not just the thrill of games like bingo, poker, and keno but also indulge in delightful dining options.
name: Club Regent Casino
address: 1425 Regent Ave W, Winnipeg, MB R2C 3B2, Canada

excerpt: Museum in a 19th-century house that belonged to Métis activist & politician Louis Riel's family.
detail_description: Riel House National Historic Site is a museum located in a 19th-century house that once belonged to the family of Louis Riel, a prominent Métis activist and politician. The site holds great historical significance in Manitoba, as it commemorates Riel's life and showcases the daily life of a Métis family in the Red River Settlement.
name: Riel House National Historic Site
address: 330 River Rd, Winnipeg, MB R2M 3Z8, Canada

excerpt: Buzzy, laid-back venture for unique flavors of homemade ice cream, including dairy-free options.
detail_description: Chaeban Ice Cream is a popular spot in Winnipeg known for its unique and homemade ice cream flavors, including dairy-free options. The modern ice cream joint has an inspiring backstory, as it was opened by Joseph Chaeban to thank the community for helping his wife's family escape from the Syrian war. With 13 flavors available, including dairy-free options like Glen Coconut, made with coconut milk and toasted coconut flakes, there's something for everyone.
name: Chaeban Ice Cream
address: 390 Osborne St, Winnipeg, MB R3L 1Z9, Canada

detail_description: Folklorama is a two-week festival held in Winnipeg, celebrating the city's rich cultural heritage. The event takes place in August and features numerous pavilions where visitors can immerse themselves in the food, music, dancing, and art of various cultures. It is considered one of the favorite yearly activities in Winnipeg and offers a unique and rewarding experience for attendees.
name: Folklorama
address: 183 Kennedy St, Winnipeg, MB R3C 1S6, Canada

detail_description: When exploring the vibrant cultural scene of Winnipeg, a visit to the Royal Winnipeg Ballet is an absolute must. As Canada’s oldest ballet company and North America’s longest-running ballet institution, it has been enchanting audiences since its inception in 1939. Nestled within the Centennial Concert Hall, this esteemed company showcases breathtaking performances that range from classic tales like 'Romeo and Juliet' to innovative contemporary works.
name: Royal Winnipeg Ballet
address: 380 Graham Ave, Winnipeg, MB R3C 4K2, Canada

detail_description: Ascend the stairs of the iconic Via Rail Union Station to tracks 1 & 2, and you'll find yourself at the Winnipeg Railway Museum. This unique museum is dedicated to preserving Manitoba's rich rail heritage, offering visitors a glimpse into where it all started.
name: Winnipeg Railway Museum
address: 123 Main St, Winnipeg, MB R3C 4V9, Canada

excerpt: This landmark footbridge over the Red River offers unique architecture & scenic views.
detail_description: The Esplanade Riel Footbridge is a striking landmark that spans the Red River, connecting downtown Winnipeg with St. Boniface. This pedestrian bridge, also known as the people path, was constructed in 2003 and is named after Louis Riel, the founder of Manitoba. Designed by Colin Douglas Stewart and Etienne Gaboury, it features a cable-stayed structure with a transversely inclined pylon standing 57 meters above the river.
name: Esplanade Riel Footbridge
address: Winnipeg, MB R2H 3J2, Canada

detail_description: Assiniboia Downs is a place where enthusiasts can come to watch live thoroughbred racing and to take part in gaming and dining opportunities. The venue is owned and operated by the Manitoba Jockey Club, making it home to the Manitoba Derby event each May through September.
name: Assiniboia Downs
address: 3975 Portage Ave, Winnipeg, MB R3K 2E9, Canada

excerpt: Huge retail complex offering department stores, boutiques, restaurants, a movie theatre & bowling.
detail_description: CF Polo Park is a vibrant retail haven located in the heart of Winnipeg, making it an ideal destination for both locals and visitors. This expansive shopping complex boasts over 200 stores, including popular brands like H&M, Zara, and Forever 21. Whether you're on the hunt for electronics or unique jewelry pieces, CF Polo Park has you covered. After a day of shopping, indulge your taste buds at one of the many restaurants or food courts available throughout the mall.
name: CF Polo Park
address: 1485 Portage Ave, Winnipeg, MB R3G 0W4, Canada

detail_description: The Winnipeg Symphony Orchestra, established in 1948, is a prominent part of the city's vibrant arts scene. Performing at the Centennial Concert Hall, the orchestra offers exceptional musical experiences for classical music enthusiasts. The venue also hosts concerts by the Winnipeg Jazz Orchestra and the Winnipeg Philharmonic Choir, catering to a broad range of musical tastes. With its rich history and commitment to diverse programming, the orchestra continues to captivate audiences with its world-class performances.
name: Winnipeg Symphony Orchestra
address: 555 Main St, Winnipeg, MB R3B 1C3, Canada

excerpt: Educational museum covering the history of Manitoba's hydroelectric power from 1870 to today.
detail_description: The Manitoba Electrical Museum offers an educational journey through the history of hydroelectric power in Manitoba, spanning from 1870 to the present day. Visitors can explore six themes that delve into electricity over the past 150 years, including a new exhibit on sustainable development and renewable energy sources. The museum features a retrofitted hydroelectric plant where guests can learn about electricity and board a replica streetcar to experience life in the 1800s before electricity.
name: Manitoba Electrical Museum
address: 680 Harrow St, Winnipeg, MB R3M 3A3, Canada

detail_description: The Trappist Monastery Provincial Heritage Park is a captivating destination located just south of Winnipeg, Manitoba. This year-round park showcases the fascinating ruins of the Lady of the Prairies Monastery, which reflect the architectural style of the early French-speaking Métis community. Visitors can explore these historic brick and stone remnants while learning about the Trappist monks who resided here until the late 1980s.
name: Trappist Monastery Provincial Heritage Park
address: 80 Rue des Ruines du Monastere, Winnipeg, MB R3V 0B1, Canada

name: English Garden
address: 460 Assiniboine Park Dr, Winnipeg, MB R3P 2N7, Canada

excerpt: Casino featuring slots, roulette, bingo & other games, plus a restaurant & lounges.
detail_description: McPhillips Station Casino, located at 484 McPhillips St., offers a variety of gaming options including slots, roulette, and bingo. The casino is designed with a Grand Railway Hotel theme and features an indoor re-creation of a historic railway village, providing visitors with a glimpse into Manitoba's past. With 800 slot machines and table games like blackjack and roulette, as well as bingo events, the casino offers recreational activities for guests.
name: McPhillips Station Casino
address: 484 McPhillips St, Winnipeg, MB R2X 2H2, Canada

excerpt: Globally inspired small plates, cocktails & craft brews in trendy, art-filled environs.
detail_description: Deer + Almond, located at 85 Princess St., is a trendy restaurant known for its globally inspired small plates, cocktails, and craft brews. Chef Mandel Hitzer's culinary skills have earned the restaurant a spot on Canada's 100 Best list multiple times since 2015. The menu features an array of unique dishes with unexpected ingredient combinations from various regions around the world, such as fried potato salad with nori and Arctic char with beet gnocchi.
name: Deer + Almond
address: 85 Princess St, Winnipeg, MB R3B 1K4, Canada

detail_description: Old Market Square in Winnipeg, Canada is a historic area surrounded by charming century-old buildings that have been repurposed into trendy restaurants, cafes, art galleries, and shops. The market's classic red-bricked architecture adds to its allure. It is a popular spot for shopping and hosts events like the Fringe festival and jazz performances during the summer. The vibrant atmosphere attracts people of all ages and cultures, making it a safe and enjoyable place to visit.
name: Old Market Square
address: Winnipeg, MB R3B 1G6, Canada

excerpt: Upmarket venue furnishing traditional local dishes with a twist, plus breakfast & veggie options.
detail_description: Feast Cafe Bistro is a renowned Indigenous-owned restaurant in Canada, offering traditional local dishes with a modern twist. Since its establishment in 2016, this upmarket venue has gained significant popularity. Owned by Chef Christa Bruneau-Guenther, a member of the Peguis First Nation, the restaurant has been featured in national publications and on Food Network Canada.
name: Feast Cafe Bistro
address: 587 Ellice Ave, Winnipeg, MB R3B 1Z7, Canada

detail_description: Nonsuch Brewing Co. is a popular microbrewery located in downtown Winnipeg, known for its ever-changing selection of craft beers and inviting taproom. The brewery offers a variety of delicious beers such as Belgian Blonde, The Tripel, Raspberry Sour, and Gose. Additionally, they have seasonal bottled beers with unique flavors. The Rain Room at Nonsuch Brewing Co.
name: Nonsuch Brewing Co.
address: 125 Pacific Ave, Winnipeg, MB R3B 0M1, Canada

excerpt: Stylish bakeshop offering cookies, cupcakes & pastries, plus a wide tea selection & espresso drinks.
detail_description: High Tea Bakery is a stylish bakeshop located in Winnipeg, Canada. Owned by Belinda, it offers an exceptional selection of cookies, cupcakes, and pastries. The bakery also boasts an extensive array of teas and espresso drinks. Visitors rave about the Imperial Cookies, Lemon Poppyseed Shortbread, Cardamom Caramel cookies, Raspberry Coconut Thumbprints, and macaroons available at High Tea Bakery.
name: High Tea Bakery
address: 2103 Portage Ave, Winnipeg, MB R3J 0L2, Canada
